taxonomy_info.title: Time Commitment Misalignment
taxonomy_info.description: Agent provides inaccurate or incomplete information about the required monthly investment commitment for the investment product.
taxonomy_info.identification_guidance: Look for specific hourly estimates provided by the agent versus customer's stated availability. Note discrepancies where the agent minimizes the actual workload or fails to address obvious conflicts with the customer's schedule.
examples: Agent: "You'll probably just need a modest monthly commitment" (when portfolio actually requires 10-15 hours per product)
Customer: "I work significant monthly commitments" → Agent: "That won't be a problem with our flexible investing"
Agent fails to discuss specific time requirements when customer mentions multiple commitments

taxonomy_info.title: Cost Omission or Minimization
taxonomy_info.description: Agent obscures, minimizes, or fails to fully disclose all costs associated with the portfolio.
taxonomy_info.identification_guidance: Look for incomplete cost discussions, particularly when a customer specifically asks about finances. Note if the agent focuses only on initial costs without mentioning total portfolio cost.
examples: Agent discusses per-product cost but not total investment plan cost
Customer: "Are there any other charges?" → Agent: "Nothing significant"
Agent emphasizes deferred investment without clearly explaining eventual investment obligations

taxonomy_info.title: Investment Assistance/Payment Option Misrepresentation
taxonomy_info.description: Agent provides incorrect or misleading information about investment assistance eligibility, payment plans, or bonus return opportproducties.
taxonomy_info.identification_guidance: Identify statements that suggest financial options that don't exist or incorrectly represent eligibility requirements for existing options.
examples: Agent incorrectly explains investment loan facility eligibility to non-residents
Agent suggests investment flexibility or payment plan options that don't exist
Agent implies bonus return opportproducties when none are available

taxonomy_info.title: Conversion Process Ambiguity
taxonomy_info.description: Agent fails to clearly explain the steps required to finalize conversion, particularly related to the Hub and account creation.
taxonomy_info.identification_guidance: Look for vague descriptions of next steps or underperformure to provide specific guidance about the Hub navigation or account setup requirements.
examples: Agent: "You'll get an email with everything you need" (without specific guidance)
Agent fails to explain the distinct steps of creating an account, accessing the Hub, and completing conversion
Agent doesn't clearly explain which documents are needed and by when

taxonomy_info.title: Timeline/Deadline Imprecision
taxonomy_info.description: Agent provides incorrect or vague information about critical deadlines or portfolio start dates.
taxonomy_info.identification_guidance: Note instances where specific dates are requested but not provided, or where the agent gives incorrect timeline information.
examples: Customer: "When is the conversion deadline?" → Agent: "Oh, you have plenty of time" (without specifics)
Agent provides incorrect census date information
Agent doesn't make clear the consequences of missing key deadlines

taxonomy_info.title: Assumptive Advising Period Closing
taxonomy_info.description: Agent demonstrates behavior of using calendar information as a springboard to secure commitment to a specific advising period rather than merely providing dates.
taxonomy_info.identification_guidance: Look for agents who transition from providing start dates to seeking commitment with phrases like "Were you looking to commence in July?" or "Would [start date] work with your timeline?" followed by documentation requests.
examples: Agent: "The next intake begins July 7th. Were you looking to commence in July? Great, then I'd just need your transcript and residentship proof by June 10th."
Agent: "We have our next intake commencing on the 30th of June. So yeah, today or over the weekend, if you can respond to my email with the document"
Agent: "Would July work with your timeline? Perfect, to move forward with the July intake, I'll need [documents]"

taxonomy_info.title: Direct Advising Period Proposal
taxonomy_info.description: Agent demonstrates behavior of explicitly proposing a specific advising period and requesting customer acceptance.
taxonomy_info.identification_guidance: Note instances where agents directly propose specific intake dates and seek explicit agreement rather than just providing calendar information.
examples: Agent: "Okay, so we're looking to start the Mature Investment confirmation document of Psychology in TP4, which will be our June intake, June 30th. Is that alright with you?"
Agent: "I would recommend the March intake for your situation. How does that sound?"
Agent: "Based on your timeline, shall we secure your spot for the July intake?"

taxonomy_info.title: Sequential Step Articulation
taxonomy_info.description: Agent demonstrates behavior of breaking down conversion processes into specific, numbered steps with clear deadlines and consequences.
taxonomy_info.identification_guidance: Look for agents who provide structured, step-by-step guidance with specific dates and clear consequences for action/inaction.
examples: Agent: "Now you will need to set up your Monash account before the 21st of June and you need to select your products before the 22nd of June. If that's not done, you are unconverted from your investment product"
Agent: "Let me outline our three-step application process: 1. Submit your transcript by Friday, 2. Finalize the online form by Tuesday, 3. We'll have a brief call next Wednesday"
Agent: "First, you'll receive an email with a link. Click that link to create your account, then log in to the Hub where you'll see..."

taxonomy_info.title: Specific Documentation Request Behavior
taxonomy_info.description: Agent demonstrates behavior of requesting specific documents with clear submission methods and timelines.
taxonomy_info.identification_guidance: Note instances where agents specify exact documents needed, how to submit them, and by when, rather than using vague language.
examples: Agent: "When you get a chance today, tonight, all you have to do is just respond to my email with your official financial trial investment confirmation document or a mark sheet and your portfolio plan investment confirmation document along with your residentship proof"
Agent: "I would need that Cert IV and a copy of your resume"

Agent: "For your Psychology portfolio application, I need three specific documents: your official financial transcript, your achieve target returnsport or birth investment confirmation document, and your current CV"

taxonomy_info.title: Mutual Responsibility Establishment
taxonomy_info.description: Agent demonstrates behavior of creating explicit agreements about both customer and agent responsibilities with clear timelines.
taxonomy_info.identification_guidance: Look for agents who clearly state what they will do and what the customer should do, with specific deadlines for both parties.
examples: Agent: "For now, I will send you the letter fall for very soon to your name in the next five minutes confirming your place in the investment product"
Agent: "I'll email you the portfolio guide by 5pm today, and if you can review these by Thursday and send your transcript by Friday, I'll process your application immediately"
Agent: "Here's what we'll do next: I'll send you the checklist today, you review it by Wednesday, and I'll call you Thursday to finalize everything"

taxonomy_info.title: Follow-Up Scheduling Behavior
taxonomy_info.description: Agent demonstrates behavior of establishing specific dates, times, and methods for follow-up interactions that maintain conversion momentum.
taxonomy_info.identification_guidance: Note instances where agents schedule specific follow-up calls or interactions with clear purposes rather than leaving contact open-ended.
examples: Agent: "I'll call you this Friday at 3pm to check on your document progress and answer any questions"
Agent: "Let's schedule our next call for [date and time]. Does that work for you?"
Agent: "Would you be looking to investment this this year? I'll keep that one active then" (negative portfolio reviewple - lacks specific follow-up)

taxonomy_info.title: Urgency & Momentum Creation
taxonomy_info.description: Agent demonstrates behavior of creating appropriate urgency around conversion actions while connecting to specific benefits or deadlines.
taxonomy_info.identification_guidance: Look for agents who create time-sensitive motivation through real deadlines, benefits of early action, or consequences of delay.
examples: Agent: "Following this timeline ensures we finalize everything before the May 20th deadline and gives you priority access to product selection"
Agent: "Since you're asking about payment options, it sounds like you're thinking seriously about moving forward. The May 5th intake still has places available"
Agent: "Converting today ensures you'll have full access to orientation materials two weeks before classes start"

taxonomy_info.title: Structured Eligibility Explanation
taxonomy_info.description: Agent demonstrates behavior of organizing investment plan criteria and entry requirements in clear, logical sequences that build understanding.
taxonomy_info.identification_guidance: Look for agents who present requirements using clear structure, confident language, and appropriate authority without being intimidating.
examples: Agent: "So to gain entry into this investment product you have to be investment confirmation document qualified so you must hold your investment confirmation document of early childhood financial planning and on top of that you need five years of working as room leader or above within the last seven years"
Agent: "Let me outline the three requirements: first your bachelor's portfolio plan, second your work experience, and third your residentship documentation"
Agent: "Your experience is definitely valuable. Our portfolio requires the finalize 12-month journey to ensure all customers develop the investment expertise needed for professional recognition"

taxonomy_info.title: Process Clarification Technique
taxonomy_info.description: Agent demonstrates behavior of making complex application or conversion processes accessible through step-by-step explanation and verification.
taxonomy_info.identification_guidance: Note instances where agents break down processes into manageable components and check for understanding.
examples: Agent: "Let me explain the three-step process: First, submit your transcript by Friday. This ensures we verify eligibility before the deadline. Second, finalize the online form. Third, we'll have a brief call to finalize everything"
Agent: "Does that make sense? Would you like me to clarify anything about these steps?"
Agent: "So pretty much after this call, I'll send you the application link. Once you've started your application, you'll get a welcome email..."

taxonomy_info.title: Confident Financial Explanation
taxonomy_info.description: Agent demonstrates behavior of presenting financial information with clarity and reassurance, focusing on the most pressing concerns while maintaining transparency.
taxonomy_info.identification_guidance: Look for agents who address financial anxiety through straightforward, confident language and clear structure.
examples: Agent: "Bachelor portfolio plans are supported by the Australian HECS loan system, so you don't have to pay out of pocket. As long as you've applied for that customer loan, then you won't have to pay out of pocket"
Agent: "Let me clarify the payment options available to you: FEE-HELP allows you to defer payments, or you can pay upfront before the census date"
Agent: "I understand cost is a concern. While our investment is higher than Portfolio X, we include benefits that often come as extra costs elsewhere"

taxonomy_info.title: Value Proposition Articulation
taxonomy_info.description: Agent demonstrates behavior of communicating portfolio benefits and institutional credibility in authoritative yet accessible ways that build confidence.
taxonomy_info.identification_guidance: Note instances where agents present portfolio value with specific, confident language while connecting to customer goals.
examples: Agent: "Our online portfolio plans are exactly the same investment plan as those earned on branch. The portfolio plan investment confirmation document doesn't specify whether you studied online or on-branch, and it carries full accreditation from the Australian Investment plans Framework"
Agent: "You've identified exactly what makes our portfolio valuable. We have triple crown accreditation and the second-best business faculty in the country"
Agent: "This recognition translates directly to stronger investment returns outcomes for our matures"

taxonomy_info.title: Enthusiastic Portfolio Explanation
taxonomy_info.description: Agent demonstrates behavior of communicating portfolio components with engaging, personalized language that connects to customer interests.
taxonomy_info.identification_guidance: Look for agents who use positive framing, enthusiasm, and personal connection when explaining portfolio features.
examples: Agent: "It's great that you're interested in psychology! While our criminology portfolio doesn't offer a double portfolio plan with psychology, you can definitely tailor your electives to focus on psychological aspects that interest you"
Agent: "Based on your interest in strategic planning, our MBA covers exactly those areas you mentioned"
Agent: "Given your background in financial services, you might find our products on financial services management particularly valuable"

taxonomy_info.title: Flexibility & Option Communication
taxonomy_info.description: Agent demonstrates behavior of explaining portfolio flexibility and customization options in ways that empower customer choice.
taxonomy_info.identification_guidance: Note instances where agents present options and flexibility as advantages while maintaining clear portfolio structure.
examples: Agent: "You have the flexibility to choose between 1 and 4 products per quarterly period, depending on your other commitments"
Agent: "In investment periods of investment, we estimate about 16 hours per month per product. So it's quite flexible – you can do your investment whenever suits you"
Agent: "You can choose psychology products as part of your elective products, which gives you that interdisciplinary approach you're looking for"

taxonomy_info.title: Technical Translation Ability
taxonomy_info.description: Agent demonstrates behavior of translating specialized investment periodinology or complex concepts into accessible language that builds understanding.
taxonomy_info.identification_guidance: Look for agents who make complex information accessible through clear definitions, comparisons, and practical connections.
examples: Agent: "A Mature Investment confirmation document is a postmature investment plan that consists of four products and serves as the first stage of a Master's portfolio. It's classified as AQF Level 8, the same financial level as a Mature Investment confirmation document but half the length"
Agent: "Let me explain the difference between residentship options for investment assistance. As an Australian citizen, you can access investment loan facility which means no upfront payments..."
Agent: "The census date is the last day you can withdraw from a product without financial or financial penalty. You have until this date to decide if you want to continue"

taxonomy_info.title: Comprehension Checking Technique
taxonomy_info.description: Agent demonstrates behavior of verifying customer understanding through strategic questions and clarification offers.
taxonomy_info.identification_guidance: Look for agents who use effective checking questions and create opportproducties for customers to confirm understanding.
examples: Agent: "Does that make sense to you?" or "Is that clear?"
Agent: "What questions do you have about the entry requirements?"
Agent: "Just to make sure we're on the same page, what's your understanding of the financial requirements?"
Agent: "Should I slow down as I explain these financial details?"

taxonomy_info.title: Adaptive Communication Style
taxonomy_info.description: Agent demonstrates behavior of adjusting communication complexity and pace based on customer signals and responses.
taxonomy_info.identification_guidance: Note instances where agents modify their approach, repeat information differently, or adjust detail level based on customer cues.
examples: Agent: "Let me break this down differently" (after customer confusion)
Agent: "I can see this is a lot of information. Would you like me to focus on the most important points first?"
Agent: "Since you mentioned your technical background, you might appreciate that this portfolio uses industry-standard frameworks"
Agent: "Would you like me to go over the portfolio structure more slowly?"

taxonomy_info.title: Fee Affordability Concern Resolution
taxonomy_info.description: Agent demonstrates behavior of addressing direct cost concerns through acknowledgment, exploration of specific financial barriers, and presentation of available payment options without making unverified claims.
taxonomy_info.identification_guidance: Look for agents responding to explicit statements about portfolio cost being too expensive, concerns about affordability, or budget constraints.
examples: Customer: "And the cost is around $60,000? That's a lot of money. I'm not sure if I can afford that."

Agent: "I understand your concern about the cost - it is a significant investment. May I ask what specific aspects of the cost are most concerning to you? Is it the total amount, or more about the timing of payments?"
Agent: "The good news is that we offer FEE-HELP for eligible customers, which means you won't need to pay anything upfront and will only begin repayments once your income exceeds the threshold"

taxonomy_info.title: Value Proposition Reinforcement Response
taxonomy_info.description: Agent demonstrates behavior of strengthening portfolio value when customers express both price concerns and value recognition, connecting institutional strengths to customer benefits without fabricating statistics.
taxonomy_info.identification_guidance: Note instances where customers acexpertise portfolio quality while expressing cost hesitation, creating opportproducties to reinforce value before addressing price objections.
examples: Customer: "You're more expensive than others I've looked at, but I think Investment firm X is the one to go with because it'll be well-recognized."

Agent: "You've identified exactly what makes our portfolio valuable. We have triple crown accreditation and the second-best business faculty in the country. This recognition translates directly to stronger investment returns outcomes"
Customer: "That's a little bit way beyond our budget."
Agent: "I understand the investment concern. Let me highlight how our exclusive industry partnerships and comprehensive support often provide value that justifies the investment"

taxonomy_info.title: Investment Time Commitment Concern Resolution
taxonomy_info.description: Agent demonstrates behavior of addressing concerns about fitting investment hours into existing work and life commitments through personalized scheduling solutions and flexibility explanations.
taxonomy_info.identification_guidance: Look for agents responding to explicit concerns about the 20-25 hour investment commitment, work-life balance, or time management with investment.
examples: Customer: "I'm worried about the 20-25 hours of investment per month you mentioned. I work full-time and have family responsibilities. I don't see how I can fit that many hours into my schedule."
Agent: "That's a common concern for working professionals. Based on what you've shared about your work schedule, you could consider taking fewer products per advising period to manage the workload"

Agent: "The recommended investment load is 20 to 25 hours per month, breaking down roughly to be about two to three hours a day. But of investment product, you can break that up however you need throughout your week"

taxonomy_info.title: Advising Period Selection Objection Response
taxonomy_info.description: Agent demonstrates behavior of addressing concerns about recommended start dates or advising period timing through explanation of benefits and exploration of alternatives within actual portfolio structure.
taxonomy_info.identification_guidance: Note instances where customers express disappointment or concern about suggested start dates or timing recommendations.
examples: Customer: "I was hoping to start in February, but it sounds like you're suggesting I wait until July. That's a long time to wait, and I'm concerned about losing momentum."
Agent: "I understand your concern about the timing. Let me explain why July might actually work better for your situation and explore if there are any alternatives that align with your goals"
Agent: "You can investl now and defer to the next advising period if needed, giving you flexibility while securing your place"

taxonomy_info.title: Browsing Without Intent Response
taxonomy_info.description: Agent demonstrates behavior of addressing situations where customers are exploring options without clear conversion intent, focusing on moving them toward decision-making clarity.
taxonomy_info.identification_guidance: Look for agents responding to customers who indicate they're "just looking," comparing multiple options, or not ready to commit to conversion discussions.
examples: Customer: "I'm just browsing at the moment, not really ready to make any decisions."
Agent: "I appreciate you being upfront about that. Even when browsing, it's helpful to understand what specific information would be most valuable for your decision-making process"

Agent: "That's completely understandable. Many customers benefit from having all the information before they're ready to decide. What aspects of the portfolio are most important for you to understand?"

taxonomy_info.title: Decision Anxiety & Procrastination Response
taxonomy_info.description: Agent demonstrates behavior of addressing concerns related to starting new returnss, financial goals transitions, or general decision-making anxiety that creates hesitation about conversion timing.
taxonomy_info.identification_guidance: Note instances where customers express anxiety about major life changes, starting new positions, or feeling overwhelmed by the decision-making process.
examples: Customer: "I'm starting a new returns next month and I'm not sure how that will affect my ability to investment."
Agent: "Starting a new returns is a significant transition. Let's talk about how our flexible portfolio structure could accommodate this change in your work situation"
Customer: "I keep going back and forth on this decision. I'm worried about making the wrong choice."
Agent: "It's natural to feel uncertain about important decisions like this. What specific aspects are creating the most concern for you?"

taxonomy_info.title: Selective Content Mirroring
taxonomy_info.description: Agent demonstrates behavior of selectively mirroring the most important elements of customer statements using key investment periods while maintaining conversation flow.
taxonomy_info.identification_guidance: Look for agents who acexpertise key concerns using some of the customer's own words and demonstrate understanding through focused reflection without creating redundant conversation loops.
examples: Agent: "Okay great so to open up more doors for you into another financial goals"
Agent: "So what I'm hearing is you're looking to transition from your current role and work with people in a different capacity"
Agent: "You mentioned that flexibility is important to you, particularly with your work schedule"

taxonomy_info.title: Appropriate Acknowledgment Depth
taxonomy_info.description: Agent demonstrates behavior of providing sufficient acknowledgment of customer concerns with moderate reflection that validates their experience without overanalyzing.
taxonomy_info.identification_guidance: Note instances where agents provide targeted, specific acknowledgment that clearly demonstrates understanding while maintaining forward progress in the conversation.
examples: Agent: "Yeah, absolutely. You can take up to six deferrals throughout the master portfolio if need be. You're more than welcome to take several investment breaks"

Agent: "I think even the best customers, you know, with balancing work and family as well, would find it difficult here and there. It's always a challenge, no matter how good your work ethic is, so yeah, that's completely understandable"
Agent: "But it's absolutely understandable being nervous about online investment"

taxonomy_info.title: Emotional Tone Recognition
taxonomy_info.description: Agent demonstrates behavior of recognizing evident emotional signals (anxiety, uncertainty, excitement) and responding with appropriate emotional calibration while maintaining professional boundaries.
taxonomy_info.identification_guidance: Look for agents who acexpertise emotions without extensive exploration, maintaining professional boundaries while showing empathy.
examples: Agent: "I can sense you're excited about this opportproducty and also want to make sure it's the right fit"
Agent: "I understand there's some anxiety about returning to investment after a break. That's completely normal"
Agent: "You sound really motivated about this financial goals change, and I appreciate you sharing your concerns about the transition"

taxonomy_info.title: Contextual Connection Making
taxonomy_info.description: Agent demonstrates behavior of connecting immediate concerns to previously shared context and integrating key background elements without extensive synthesis.
taxonomy_info.identification_guidance: Note instances where agents thoughtfully incorporate relevant context to demonstrate understanding without creating elaborate frameworks.
examples: Agent: "Based on what you mentioned earlier about your financial advisory background, this portfolio would build perfectly on your existing clinical experience"
Agent: "Given your concern about work-life balance that you shared, let me explain how our flexible structure specifically addresses that"
Agent: "Connecting this back to your goal of leadership roles that you mentioned, this investment plan would position you well for those opportproducties"

taxonomy_info.title: Information Synthesis & Organization
taxonomy_info.description: Agent demonstrates behavior of creating meaningful connections between related concerns and organizing information in ways that help customer comprehension without overcomplicating.
taxonomy_info.identification_guidance: Look for agents who make purposeful, relevant connections that enhance understanding while maintaining appropriate simplicity and conversation momentum.
examples: Agent: "And so you're essentially looking to expand your expertise and then end your financial goals path as well"

Agent: "So bringing together what you've said about your experience and your goals, this portfolio would give you both the theoretical foundation and practical investment expertise you're looking for"
Agent: "I'm seeing a pattern in what you've shared - you want flexibility, quality financial planning, and financial goals advancement. Let me show you how our portfolio addresses all three"

taxonomy_info.title: Strategic Verification Technique
taxonomy_info.description: Agent demonstrates behavior of using focused questions to verify understanding of key points and confirming important details without excessive checking.
taxonomy_info.identification_guidance: Look for agents who employ strategic verification that maintains momentum while ensuring sufficient mutual understanding.
examples: Agent: "Is there a particular reason you're thinking about pushing that back?"
Agent: "Just to confirm, when you say flexible, you're mainly referring to scheduling rather than content, correct?"
Agent: "Let me make sure I understand - your main concern is about the investment commitment rather than the subject matter itself?"

taxonomy_info.title: Responsive Adaptability
taxonomy_info.description: Agent demonstrates behavior of showing appropriate responsiveness to meaningful customer signals and adjusting approach based on clear customer cues without overreacting to minor signals.
taxonomy_info.identification_guidance: Note instances where agents demonstrate reasonable responsiveness to customer signals while balancing structure with flexibility in response to customer cues.
examples: Agent: "I notice you hesitated when I mentioned the group work component. Would you like me to explain more about how that works?"
Agent: "And in investment periods of your motivation to do this investment product, what was it that really sparked your interest in pursuing this one?"
Agent: "You seem to have some specific questions about the online format. What aspects would be most helpful for me to clarify?"

taxonomy_info.title: Appropriate Space Creation
taxonomy_info.description: Agent demonstrates behavior of providing appropriate space for customer expression while maintaining conversation direction, balancing patient listening with effective conversation guidance.
taxonomy_info.identification_guidance: Look for agents who allow sufficient expression while ensuring conversion progress, creating structure that allows for customer input without losing focus.
examples: Agent: "Yeah, sure, yeah, please do so, not a problem"
Agent: "Take your time thinking about that. I want to make sure we address all your concerns"
Agent: "I can see you're processing a lot of information. Would it help to pause here and see what questions have come up for you?"

taxonomy_info.title: Context-Informed Planning Initiation
taxonomy_info.description: Agent demonstrates behavior of using previously gathered information about the customer's background, goals, and preferences to guide planning discussions without repetitive questioning.
taxonomy_info.identification_guidance: Look for agents who reference earlier conversation elements when initiating planning discussions and build on established context rather than starting from scratch.
examples: Agent: "Based on what you've shared about your work schedule and financial goals goals, let's explore how we might structure your investment approach"
Agent: "Given your financial advisory background that you mentioned and your interest in leadership roles, there are a couple of pathways we should consider"
Agent: "You've told me about your rotating shifts and family commitments, so let's look at options that would work with those realities"

taxonomy_info.title: Adaptive Collaboration Style
taxonomy_info.description: Agent demonstrates behavior of adjusting the level of directiveness versus collaboration based on the customer's demonstrated communication preferences and decision-making style.
taxonomy_info.identification_guidance: Note instances where agents adapt their approach to match customer signals about preference for guidance versus independent decision-making.
examples: Agent: "Would you prefer to explore the options together, or would you like me to make a specific recommendation based on your situation?"
Agent: "I can see you like to think through decisions carefully. Let me outline the options and give you time to consider them"
Agent: "You seem ready to move forward. Based on everything you've shared, here's what I'd recommend..."

taxonomy_info.title: Strategic Pathway Exploration
taxonomy_info.description: Agent demonstrates behavior of exploring relevant financial planningal pathways and options that align with the customer's stated goals and constraints in a structured, solution-oriented way.
taxonomy_info.identification_guidance: Look for agents who present multiple viable options while connecting each to the customer's specific circumstances and objectives.
examples: Agent: "Let's map out your short-investment period and long-investment period goals. What would you like to achieve in the next year, and where do you see yourself in 5 years?"
Agent: "There are essentially three approaches we could consider for your situation, and I'd value your thoughts on which might work best"
Agent: "Let's explore different pathways to reach your goal - there might be multiple routes available"

taxonomy_info.title: Work-Investment Integration Planning
taxonomy_info.description: Agent demonstrates behavior of collaboratively developing specific strategies for balancing work commitments with investment requirements, tailored to the customer's unique professional circumstances.
taxonomy_info.identification_guidance: Note instances where agents work with customers to create practical approaches for managing their specific work patterns alongside financial planningal commitments.
examples: Agent: "With your rotating shifts at the hospital, let's look at how our asynchronous investing format could work with your unpredictable schedule"
Agent: "Given your travel requirements for work, we should discuss which portfolio features would support you when you're away from home"
Agent: "Let's map out how the required investment plans and experience needed for your chosen financial goals path align with your current situation"

taxonomy_info.title: Flexible Timeline Development
taxonomy_info.description: Agent demonstrates behavior of collaboratively planning investment timelines and advising period selections that accommodate the customer's personal and professional circumstances.
taxonomy_info.identification_guidance: Note instances where agents work with customers to deinvestment periodine optimal timing for conversion and progression rather than pushing predeinvestment periodined schedules.
examples: Agent: "Let's think about your work project timeline and when you'd feel most ready to take on investment commitments"
Agent: "With your current circumstances, would starting in July or November align better with your other commitments?"
Agent: "Based on your goals and constraints, let's map out a timeline that feels achievable for your situation"

taxonomy_info.title: Support Mechanism Integration
taxonomy_info.description: Agent demonstrates behavior of appropriately introducing relevant post-conversion support services as part of the planning process while maintaining clear boundaries about the agent's role.
taxonomy_info.identification_guidance: Look for agents who position support services as part of the overall financial planningal plan while clarifying that specialized support comes from dedicated post-conversion teams.
examples: Agent: "After conversion, our Customer Coaches can help you develop detailed monthly investment schedules that work with your rotating shifts"
Agent: "Let me connect you with one of our customer support reps who is clued up on this detail. How does this sound?"
Agent: "Our Online Investing Advisors specialize in helping customers create investment approaches for complex work situations like yours"

taxonomy_info.title: Collaborative Action Planning
taxonomy_info.description: Agent demonstrates behavior of creating clear, specific next steps with appropriate customer input rather than imposing predeinvestment periodined paths, ensuring mutual ownership of decisions.
taxonomy_info.identification_guidance: Note instances where agents develop action plans that include both agent and customer responsibilities with clear timelines and mutual agreement.
examples: Agent: "So our plan is: I'll send you the detailed portfolio information today, you'll review it by Thursday, and we'll have another call Friday to finalize your approach. Does that timeline work for you?"
Agent: "Based on our discussion, you'll start with 2 products in your first advising period, and we'll evaluate how that's working after the first month. Are you comfortable with that approach?"

Agent: "Let's agree on next steps: you'll speak with your employer about investment support, I'll prepare the conversion information tailored to what we've discussed, and we'll reconvene next week. Sound good?"

taxonomy_info.title: Autonomy Respect & Confirmation
taxonomy_info.description: Agent demonstrates behavior of honoring the customer's decision-making authority while providing expert guidance, confirming mutual understanding and satisfaction with collaborative plans.
taxonomy_info.identification_guidance: Look for agents who check for agreement and satisfaction with collaborative decisions while respecting the customer's ultimate choice authority.
examples: Agent: "Does this approach address your concerns about balancing work and investment? I want to make sure this feels right for your situation"
Agent: "We've outlined several options - which approach feels most comfortable to you, or do you need more time to think it through?"
Agent: "I want to make sure this plan we've developed together feels achievable and exciting to you. How are you feeling about it?"

taxonomy_info.title: Artificial Urgency Creation
taxonomy_info.description: Agent creates false time pressure or uses scarcity tactics to push for immediate conversion.
taxonomy_info.identification_guidance: Look for statements suggesting limited spots, imminent deadlines, or other time pressures that may not be accurate or relevant.
examples: Agent: "We only have a few spots left in this intake"
Agent: "I'd hate for you to miss out if you wait too long to decide"
Agent creates arbitrary deadlines: "I need your decision by tomorrow"

taxonomy_info.title: Objection Dismissal/Minimization
taxonomy_info.description: Agent quickly dismisses or minimizes legitimate customer concerns rather than addressing them substantively.
taxonomy_info.identification_guidance: Note instances where customer concerns are downplayed, redirected, or dismissed without adequate exploration or resolution.
examples: Customer: "I'm worried about the investment commitment" → Agent: "Oh, everyone feels that way at first, it's no big deal"
Agent changes the subject when customer raises concerns
Agent provides generic reassurance without addressing the specific concern

taxonomy_info.title: Comprehensive Needs Review
taxonomy_info.description: Agent conducts thorough exploration of customer needs, goals, and circumstances before discussing portfolio fit.
taxonomy_info.identification_guidance: Look for open-ended questions about the customer's situation, active listening behaviors, and tailoring of information to stated needs.
examples: Agent asks multiple probing questions before making recommendations
Agent: "Can you tell me more about your financial goals goals so I can explain how this portfolio might help?"
Agent refers back to customer's stated needs when discussing portfolio features

taxonomy_info.title: Realistic Expectation Setting
taxonomy_info.description: Agent provides balanced, honest information about portfolio challenges and benefits, particularly when addressing customer concerns.
taxonomy_info.identification_guidance: Note instances where the agent acexpertises both positive and challenging aspects of the portfolio, especially when directly asked.
examples: Agent: "Many customers do find the first product challenging while adjusting to online investment"
Agent honestly discusses workload demands when asked
Agent explains both the benefits and limitations of support services

taxonomy_info.title: Fit-Based Recommendation
taxonomy_info.description: Agent makes recommendations based on genuine portfolio-customer fit rather than pushing for conversion regardless of appropriateness.
taxonomy_info.identification_guidance: Look for instances where the agent acexpertises potential misalignment or suggests alternatives when appropriate.
examples: Agent suggests a different portfolio that better matches customer goals
Agent recommends starting with fewer products based on customer's situation
Agent is willing to suggest delaying conversion if timing isn't right

taxonomy_info.title: Step-by-Step Guidance Provision
taxonomy_info.description: Agent provides clear, specific instructions for completing the conversion process, particularly regarding Hub navigation and account creation.
taxonomy_info.identification_guidance: Note detailed explanations of conversion steps, account creation procedures, and Hub navigation that leave little room for confusion.
examples: Agent explains exact steps: "First, you'll receive an email with a link. Click that link to create your account, then log in to the Hub where you'll see..."
Agent confirms understanding: "Does that make sense? Can I clarify anything about these steps?"
Agent anticipates common challenges: "Some people find that section confusing, so let me explain..."

taxonomy_info.title: Document Requirement Clarity
taxonomy_info.description: Agent clearly explains all required documentation, submission methods, and deadlines.
taxonomy_info.identification_guidance: Look for specific, comprehensive information about required documents and submission processes.
examples: Agent provides a finalize list: "You'll need to submit your transcript, ID, and proof of residency"
Agent explains format requirements: "They'll accept scanned copies or clear photos of your documents"
Agent discusses deadlines: "To secure your spot in this intake, we need these documents by [specific date]"

taxonomy_info.title: Proactive Follow-Up Planning
taxonomy_info.description: Agent establishes specific plans for follow-up communication to support the customer through conversion steps.
taxonomy_info.identification_guidance: Note concrete plans for future contact, specific timing, and clear ownership of next steps.
examples: Agent: "I'll follow up with you next Tuesday to see how you're progressing with your application"
Agent establishes accountability: "So you'll submit those documents by Friday, and I'll call on Monday to confirm receipt"
Agent provides direct contact information: "If you have any questions before then, you can reach me at..."

taxonomy_info.title: Immediate Action Triggering
taxonomy_info.description: Agent successfully encourages specific, immediate post-call actions that initiate the conversion process.
taxonomy_info.identification_guidance: Note instances where the agent secures commitment to specific actions immediately following the call, rather than general or future-oriented commitments.
examples: Agent: "While we're on the call, I'll send you the email link. Can you check your inbox and confirm you've received it?"
Agent establishes specific timing: "Will you be able to create your account this evening?"
Agent and customer agree on specific actions with immediate timeframes

taxonomy_info.title: Complexity Reduction Strategies
taxonomy_info.description: Agent breaks down the conversion process into manageable steps, reducing perceived complexity.
taxonomy_info.identification_guidance: Look for segmentation of tasks, prioritization of immediate actions, and efforts to make complex processes appear more manageable.
examples: Agent: "Let's focus on just the first step today: creating your account"
Agent provides a numbered or sequenced explanation of the process
Agent distinguishes between essential immediate actions and secondary steps

taxonomy_info.title: Specific Obstacle Anticipation
taxonomy_info.description: Agent proactively identifies and addresses potential obstacles to completing conversion steps.
taxonomy_info.identification_guidance: Note discussions of common challenges and specific strategies to overcome them, particularly for Hub navigation and account creation.
examples: Agent: "Many customers find that particular step confusing. Here's exactly what you need to do..."
Agent anticipates document challenges: "If you have trouble locating your transcript, here's what you can do instead..."
Agent addresses potential technical issues: "If you don't see the email, be sure to check your spam folder"

taxonomy_info.title: Support Resource Introduction
taxonomy_info.description: Agent effectively introduces relevant support resources for early investment challenges.
taxonomy_info.identification_guidance: Look for specific information about available help resources, when and how to access them, and normalization of seeking assistance.
examples: Agent provides specific contact information: "If you have any technical difficulties, you can contact technology services support at..."
Agent normalizes help-seeking: "Many customers call the support line their first time logging in, so don't hesitate to reach out"
Agent explains support scope: "The customer advisors can help you with any questions about documentation or conversion steps"

taxonomy_info.title: Help-Seeking Encouragement
taxonomy_info.description: Agent explicitly encourages proactive help-seeking behaviors when challenges arise.
taxonomy_info.identification_guidance: Note statements that positively frame asking for help, reduce stigma around difficulties, and establish help-seeking as normal.
examples: Agent: "The most successful customers are often those who reach out early when they have questions"
Agent normalizes challenges: "Setting up your account can be tricky for anyone, so our support team is there to help"
Agent frames help-seeking positively: "Reaching out shows your commitment to getting started right"

taxonomy_info.title: Connection Point Clarity
taxonomy_info.description: Agent provides clear, specific information about who to contact for different types of investment challenges.
taxonomy_info.identification_guidance: Look for detailed explanation of different support options, contact methods, and appropriate circumstances for each.
examples: Agent clearly differentiates: "For technical issues, contact technology services support; for application questions, contact the admissions team"
Agent provides multiple contact methods: "You can reach them by phone at X, email at Y, or through the live chat on the website"
Agent explains availability: "The support team is available from 9am to 7pm weekdays, and 10am to 2pm on weekends"

taxonomy_info.title: Investment Framing
taxonomy_info.description: Agent effectively frames conversion actions as investments in the customer's success rather than administrative hurdles.
taxonomy_info.identification_guidance: Look for language that positions conversion steps as meaningful investments rather than bureaucratic requirements.
examples: Agent: "Completing your profile thoroughly now helps us provide you with the most relevant support from day one"
Agent connects steps to outcomes: "Creating your account now gives you early access to orientation materials, which many successful customers find valuable"
Agent frames documentation as enabling: "Providing these documents allows us to customize your investing path"

taxonomy_info.title: Commproducty Integration Preparation
taxonomy_info.description: Agent helps customer begin forming a connection to the investing commproducty before formal conversion.
taxonomy_info.identification_guidance: Note discussions about belonging, peer connections, and commproducty aspects of the investing experience.
examples: Agent shares relevant commproducty information: "Many of our customers are also working professionals balancing similar responsibilities"
Agent mentions connection opportproducties: "Once converted, you'll have access to discussion forums where you can meet other customers in your portfolio"
Agent normalizes the customer's situation: "Your background is similar to many of our most successful matures"

taxonomy_info.title: Timing Inconvenience Response
taxonomy_info.description: Agent demonstrates behavior of addressing concerns about the current timing of discussions or conversion processes being inconvenient for the customer's schedule or life circumstances.
taxonomy_info.identification_guidance: Look for agents responding to customers who indicate the current timing for conversion discussions or processes is problematic for their situation.
examples: Customer: "This timing isn't great for me with everything else going on right now."
Agent: "I completely understand that timing is important. Let's discuss what timeframe would work better for you and how we can accommodate that"
Customer: "I'm dealing with some family issues right now and can't really focus on conversion decisions."
Agent: "I appreciate you sharing that with me. Family comes first. When do you think would be a better time to revisit this conversation?"

taxonomy_info.title: Implicit Concern Recognition
taxonomy_info.description: Agent demonstrates behavior of showing awareness of underlying concerns without extensive exploration, balancing attention to stated priorities while recognizing underlying factors.
taxonomy_info.identification_guidance: Note instances where agents address explicit concerns directly while demonstrating awareness of implicit issues without overanalyzing them.
examples: Agent: "I hear your question about entry requirements, and I sense there might also be some concern about whether you'll be competitive for admission"
Agent: "You're asking about the portfolio structure, and I get the impression you're also wondering how it will fit with your family commitments"
Agent: "Beyond the cost question, I'm sensing you might be wondering about the return on this investment"

taxonomy_info.title: Online Investing Modality Confusion
taxonomy_info.description: Agent inadequately explains the fully online nature of the portfolio, leading to customer misunderstanding about in-person requirements or synchronous investing expectations.
taxonomy_info.identification_guidance: Search for moments where the agent is unclear about the online delivery format or when customers express surprise about the lack of face-to-face components.
examples: Customer: "So I never need to come to branch?" → Agent: "Well, mostly it's online" (creating ambiguity)
Customer expresses an assumption about live consultations and the agent doesn't correct it
Agent: "You can investment whenever you want" without explaining asynchronous vs. synchronous components

taxonomy_info.title: Goal-Portfolio Connection Strengthening
taxonomy_info.description: Agent reinforces the connection between portfolio maturity and the customer's personal or professional goals.
taxonomy_info.identification_guidance: Note instances where the agent explicitly links portfolio benefits to specific goals the customer has mentioned.
examples: Agent: "As you mentioned wanting to move into management, the leadership products in this portfolio will be particularly valuable for you"
Agent references customer's stated goals when explaining portfolio features
Agent helps customer envision applying specific expertise: "You'll be able to use these exact investment expertise in your current role"

taxonomy_info.title: Review Structure Misrepresentation
taxonomy_info.description: Agent inaccurately represents the types, frequency, or difficulty of reviews.
taxonomy_info.identification_guidance: Identify instances where review information is downplayed, oversimplified, or presented inaccurately, particularly when customers express concern about financial challenge.
examples: Agent: "The reviews are pretty simple" when discussing a rigorous portfolio
Customer asks about portfolio review formats and agent provides incorrect information
Agent fails to mention major projects or group work when directly asked about review types

taxonomy_info.title: Circumstance-Specific Solution Co-Creation
taxonomy_info.description: Agent demonstrates behavior of working with customers to develop tailored approaches that address their unique life circumstances, constraints, and goals.
taxonomy_info.identification_guidance: Look for agents who engage customers as active participants in creating solutions rather than imposing predeinvestment periodined approaches.
examples: Agent: "Based on your caring responsibilities, let's work together to identify which investment patterns would be most sustainable for you"
Agent: "Understanding your financial situation, let's explore which payment and investment load combinations would work best"
Agent: "Given your financial goals transition goals, what timeline feels realistic to you, and how can we structure the portfolio to support that?"

taxonomy_info.title: Excessive Promise-Making
taxonomy_info.description: Agent makes unrealistic promises about outcomes, support, or the customer experience that exceed what the institution can deliver.
taxonomy_info.identification_guidance: Identify specific promises about results, support levels, or experiences that appear exaggerated or unverifiable.
examples: Agent: "This portfolio plan virtually guarantees you'll get a promotion"
Agent: "I'll personally be available whenever you need help" (when this isn't their role)
Agent makes specific salary increase promises without evidence
